                        <decoDesc><summary>The volume contains 405 illustrations, a majority of the small, early 15th
                            century style of Muzaffarid-era Shiraz. Another similar, complete manuscript held in the British
                            Library (Add. 23564), contains 453 images. This volume likely contained another 21 illustrations on folios now missing folios at the beginning and end of this volume, 
                            as well as another 11 or so that adorned the replaced folios 49 to 56. Considered together, when first completed the volume potentially contained 436 illlustrations totalled.</summary>
                            <decoNote type="illustration"><label>Illustrations:</label> For a complete description, see Robinson, pp. 1–69, nos. 1–404.
                                </decoNote>
                            <decoNote type="headpiece"><label>Illumination:</label>
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote type="marginal"><label>Ruling:</label>
                                
                            </decoNote>
                            
                        </decoDesc>
                        <bindingDesc><binding notBefore="1750" notAfter="1875"><p>Restored in 19th-century Iran.  <hi rend="italic">mīnāyī</hi> (enamel-like) binding</p>
                            <decoNote><p>Recessed decorations features blocked central scalloped mandorlas with flanking medallions, and surrrounding margins in <material>gold</material>, with brightly painted flowers, known as <hi rend="italic">Mīnāyī</hi> (enamalled) on account of the shiny appearance of the paint. For a comparable example, see Harvard University Art Museums, description by Mihan, and references by Bayānī and Ardakānī</p></decoNote>
                                <p>
                                    
                                </p>
                        </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
